                  <interp source="ph_023" xml:id="ana_023">
                     <desc>
                        In her memoir <ref target="acdh:amp-transcript__0062.xml">"The Years in Austria"</ref> (14-15), <rs type="person" ref="#amp_person_2">Stella Musulin</rs> relates the lines <quote source="acdh:amp-transcript__0038.xml">"(In what bars are they welcome? / What girls marry them?)"</quote> in the version of <rs type="person" ref="#amp_person_1">W. H. Auden</rs>'s poem <rs type="lit_work" ref="#lit_work_id_61">"Joseph Weinheber"</rs> from 15 March 1965 to a passage (<quote source="acdh:amp-transcript__0002.xml">"Where do the torturers come from? What class? Whom do they marry? <del>Have you ever met one<unclear>?</unclear></del> To what pubs do they go?"</quote>) in the poet's <ref target="acdh:amp-transcript__0002.xml">letter to her from 23 December 1964</ref>: "When I told <rs type="person" ref="#amp_person_4">Chester</rs> about how Auden's letter to me had made its own infinitesimal contribution to English literature, Chester snapped: 'Wystan never wastes anything!'"
                        <bibl sameAs="acdh:amp-transcript__0062.xml">
                           <citedRange unit="page" from="14" to="15"/>
                        </bibl>
                     </desc>
                     <respons resp="dgrigoriou smayer tfruehwrith" locus="value"/>
                     <certainty cert="high" locus="value"/>
                  </interp>
                  <interp source="ph_027" xml:id="ana_027">
